{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475986"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:39:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:39:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13109"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13109"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.28,0.08,0.56,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5546"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104331"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5546"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13109"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86660"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4956"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12229"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44831"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44985"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104331"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old boy has come to the General Practice clinic with his father; the family are recent migrants from Thailand. The child has a severe developmental disability. He recently had a skin infection that resolved within a couple of days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, the father is concerned about infection risks for the future. The child did not have any immunisations given in Thailand but has received the standard vaccinations for his age according to the Australian National Immunisation Schedule.  The father is wondering if he should be given any additional vaccinations based on his health profile. The child\u0027s recent blood tests for immigration showed normal liver function, renal function, blood sugar; electrolytes, vitamin levels, and haematological tests were normal. He is negative for HIV and other sexually transmitted infections. He has not travelled recently and there is no intention of travelling in the near future.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following vaccinations is recommended for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cholera","Hepatitis A","Japanese encephalitis","Pneumococcal (23vPPV)","Typhoid"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of developmental disabilities is an indication for the provision of additional vaccinations: the \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatitis A\u003C/strong\u003E vaccination and hepatitis B vaccination. Hepatitis A vaccination schedule is two doses recommended with an interval of at least six months.  Furthermore, this family has recently arrived from Thailand, which is an area in which Hepatitis A is endemic. The child could either be given the vaccination regardless or be tested first for hepatitis A immunity.  It would not be harmful to give the hepatitis A vaccination if the patient had contracted hepatitis A during his earlier childhood in Thailand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholera\u003C/strong\u003E vaccination is typically recommended for people who will be expected to travel in areas in which cholera is endemic. This child is not planning to travel and cholera is not endemic in Thailand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJapanese encephalitis\u003C/strong\u003E vaccination is typically recommended for those who are travelling in regions where this infection is prevalent, and laboratory workers who work with/around the causative microbe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EPneumococcal (23vPPV)\u003C/strong\u003E vaccine is typically recommended for those who have a pre-disposing risk factor for pneumococcal disease. Examples of such risks are the following: past pneumococcal disease, asplenia, immunocompromising conditions (such as HIV, haematological malignancies), cerebrospinal fluid leak, chronic respiratory conditions, chronic renal conditions, cardiac disease, chronic liver disease, infant being born less than 28 weeks, diabetes, smoking, heavy alcohol usage, and Trisomy 21. Having a developmental disability and foetal alcohol syndrome is not included in the risk factors for receiving funded pneumococcal vaccination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etyphoid\u003C/strong\u003E vaccination is not recommended for this patient with the developmental disability. It is specifically recommended for those in the military, laboratory workers, and those travelling to endemic regions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Having a developmental disability is an indication for vaccination against Hepatitis A and Hepatitis B. Chronic liver disease is also an indication for these vaccinations."],"references":["Australian Government. Meningococcal vaccine. Accessed on April 9, 2024. Retrieved from: https://www.health.gov.au/topics/immunisation/immunisation-services/meningococcal-immunisation-service-0","Australian Government. Hepatitis A. Accessed on April 9, 2024. Retrieved from: https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/contents/vaccine-preventable-diseases/hepatitis-a","National Centre for Immunisation Research. Immunisation recommendations for people with risk factors for certain vaccine preventable diseases. 2024. Accessed on April 9, 2024. Retrieved from: https://ncirs.org.au/sites/default/files/2024-01/NCIRS_Immunisation%20schedule_People%20with%20risk%20factors%20for%20certain%20vaccine%20preventable%20diseases_January%202024_0.pdf","Australian Government. Japanese encephalitis. Accessed on April 9, 2024. Retrieved from:  https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/contents/vaccine-preventable-diseases/japanese-encephalitis","Australian Government. Risk conditions for pneumococcal disease. Accessed on April 9, 2024. Retrieved from:  https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/resources/tables/list-risk-conditions-for-pneumococcal-disease","Australian Government. Typhoid fever. Accessed on April 9, 2024. Retrieved from: https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/contents/vaccine-preventable-diseases/typhoid-fever","Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Thailand. Accessed on May 13, 2024. Retrieved from: https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/destinations/traveler/none/thailand"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86660"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13109"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86660"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-31T23:48:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-31T23:48:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5546"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104331"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type